  "text": "[12] In the baseline model (magma chamber depth is 2 km, volume is 50 km 3 , D/H = 2, and host rock permeability is 10 À16 m 2 ; Figure 1 ) an initial peak in the surface discharge occurring at only a few hundred years following magma emplacement is due to thermal pressurization [CITATION_1] . Its peak value is not significantly greater than discharges that occur later in the model. The extremely short-lived nature of this effect, which is less extreme for higher host rock permeabilities, contributes negligibly to the total, timeintegrated mass of water produced by the system (total discharge), which we assume to be of primary importance in valley erosion. Additionally, thermal pressurization may be weaker in the more realistic case of a finite duration intrusion process.",
